results.description: Anzac Cove Area (Gallipoli). 1915-11-28. Two wounded Turkish soldiers lie on stretchers after being dragged behind their line by members of No. 2 Field Company, Royal Australian Engineers. They had fallen over the Australian tunnel during fighting the previous night and had lain wounded in the extremely cold conditions dressed only in khaki drill. Note the graves being dug in the background and the crosses of the nearby cemetery. (Original housed in AWM Archive Store)

results.description: 1st Battalion troops having taken 80 yards of a Turkish trench, waiting near Jacob's Trench for relief by the 7th Battalion.  Identified from left: Captain Cecil Duncan Sasse, (with eyes bandaged, later Lieutenant Colonel, DSO and Bar, MID); 2211 Private George Wood (with legs crossed); 2173 Private Martin Maher, (smoking pipe); 2138 Private Walter Finn (hands near rifle muzzle); unidentified. These men had been fighting continuously from the beginning of the Lone Pine attack on 6 August 1915.

results.description: A group of five officers in a gully on the Gallipoli Peninsula. Identified left to right (seated, nearest the camera): Captain George Frederick Wootten, Captain Cecil Duncan Sasse and Major Frederick James Kindon, all of the 1st Battalion; possibly Major William Davidson, 1st Battalion, who died of wounds on 19 August 1915. Standing: General William Riddell Birdwood, Officer Commanding the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps. The wooden crate on the far right contains or contained 50 pounds of biscuits.

results.description: Group portrait of regimental officers of the 7th Australian Light Horse Regiment (7ALH), preparatory to revisiting Gallipoli. Identified, front row, third from left, probably Major Luke Bice, and fourth from left is Lieutenant Colonel John Dalyell Richardson DSO Order of the Nile, 3rd Class, Commanding Officer. In late 1918, members of 7ALH were chosen to represent the regiment on a tour of the old battlefields of Gallipoli. The group, predominantly made up of Gallipoli veterans, disembarked on the peninsula on 4 December 1918.

results.description: Gallipoli Peninsula, Turkey. c. 1 August 1915. Anzac Cove is here depicted as it was in July and August 1915. At this time the Australians and New Zealanders (Anzacs) were well established at their base, but although the Turks had been pushed well back into the interior the spot was never absolutely free from shells which came from the Turkish guns hidden in the distant hills.

results.description: Gallipoli Peninsula, Turkey. November 1915. The cemetery in Shrapnel Gully. The men paid very great attention to this and other cemeteries during the last few days of the occupation. This cemetery was near the mouth of the Gully. Main Sap can be seen running past the left hand side of it. In the distance are Deadman's Ridge and Turkish position on Chess Board, from which the Turks sniped down the valley.

results.description: The remains of trenches and overhead cover at Lone Pine from which both sides would throw bombs at each other. The Turkish monument, which marks the spot where the Anzac August 1915 advance at Lone Pine was stopped by the Turks, is on the left.  Major Zeki Bey, a Turkish soldier who fought at Anzac during 1915 is standing on the skyline at left.  One of a series of photographs taken on the Gallipoli Peninsula under the direction of Captain C E W Bean of the Australian Historical Mission, during the months of February and March, 1919.
